{{about|the city|the bug genus|Ficana (insect)}}
'''Ficana''' was an ancient city of [[Latium]],<ref name="Fischer-Hansen1990">{{cite book|author=Tobias Fischer-Hansen|title=Scavi di Ficana: Topografia generale|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=j2MMAQAAMAAJ|year=1990|publisher=Istituto poligrafico e Zecca dello Stato, Libreria dello Stato}}</ref> which figures in [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] history only on the occasion of its conquest by [[Ancus Marcius]], who is said to have moved the inhabitants to [[Rome]], and destroyed the city itself. ([[Livy]] i. 33; Dionys. iii. 38, where the editions have ''Fidenae'', but there is little doubt that the event referred to is the same related by Livy.) It is certain that it was never repeopled: its name is found in [[Pliny the Elder|Pliny]]'s list of the extinct cities of Latium (iii. 5. s. 9), and is noticed also by Festus (''v. Puilia Saxa'') as a place no longer in existence.  The latter passage, however, affords us a clue to its position; according to [[Marcus Antistius Labeo]] there cited, it was situated on the [[Via Ostiensis]],<ref name="Ostia1980">{{cite book|author=Soprintendenza archeologica di Ostia|title=Ficana: una pietra miliare sulla strada per Roma : mostra itinerante degli scavi italo nordici a Ficana (Acilia), 1975-1980|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cmMMAQAAMAAJ|date=c. 1980|publisher=Libreria Editrice}}</ref> eleven miles from Rome, and apparently immediately adjoining the [[Tiber]], on which it had a port, at a place called by [[Fabius Pictor]] the ''Puilia Saxa''.  The city's site is in the commune of Rome near Acilia, on the via Ostiense between Rome and Ostia.<ref name="Fischer-HansenOstia1990">{{cite book|author1=Tobias Fischer-Hansen|author2=Italy. Soprintendenza archeologica di Ostia|title=Scavi di Ficana: Il periodo protostorico e arcaico. pt. 1. Le zone di scavo 3b-c|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sGQMAQAAMAAJ|year=1990|publisher=Istituto poligrafico e Zecca dello Stato, Libreria dello Stato}}</ref>

